Tutorial: embedding learning of malignant cell expression using BayesPrism

Tinyi Chu

  • Introduction
  • Selecting the number of malignant programs K.
  • Run embedding learning
  • Downstream analysis

Note: if you use BayesPrism in published research, please cite:

Chu, T., Wang, Z., Peer, D. Danko, C. G. Cell type and gene expression deconvolution with BayesPrism enables Bayesian integrative analysis across bulk and single-cell RNA sequencing in oncology. Nat Cancer 3, 505517 (2022). https://doi.org/10.1038/s43018-022-00356-3

Introduction

BayesPrism contains an optional embedding learning module to identify gene expression patterns that arise commonly among bulk RNA-seq samples after removal of nonmalignant cells infiltrating the tumor. The mathematical formulation is to factor out the observed #bulk-by-#genes matrix to

, such that the tumor expression is factored out to multiple malignant gene expression programs.

Selecting the number of malignant programs K.

Similar to other matrix factorization problems, user needs to specify K. One potential way of selecting K is to scan a range of K values by running non-negative matrix factorizing (NMF) over the (normalized) deconvolved gene expression of malignant cells. K can be chosen by various metrics afterwards.

  • Load the BayesPrism package
suppressWarnings(library(BayesPrism))
#> Loading required package: snowfall
#> Loading required package: snow
#> Loading required package: NMF
#> Loading required package: pkgmaker
#> Loading required package: registry
#> Loading required package: rngtools

#> NMF - BioConductor layer [OK] | Shared memory capabilities [NO: bigmemory] | Cores 71/72
#>   To enable shared memory capabilities, try: install.extras('
#> NMF
#> ')
  • Load the results from deconvolution
load("bp.res.rdata")
  • Scan a range of K values (from 2 to 12) using nmf. This may take a while.
Z.tum.norm <- t(bp.res@reference.update@psi_mal)
estim.Z.tum.norm <- nmf(Z.tum.norm, rank=2:12, seed=123456)
  • Visualize various metrics against K.
plot(estim.Z.tum.norm)

  • Plot consensus maps for different K.
consensusmap(estim.Z.tum.norm, labCol=NA, labRow=NA)

  • We choose K=5 based on these plots.

Run embedding learning

# This may take long time to complete...
ebd.res <- learn.embedding.nmf (bp = bp.res, #bp.res needs to be run under the tumor mode.
                                  K = 5,
                                  cycle = 20, #EM typically converges in 50 cycles. set to 20 for demo  
                                  compute.elbo = T) #set to TRUE if needs to compute ELBO, otherwise to FALSE which may slightly speed up the computation

#>   .. ..$ : chr [1:5] "program-1" "program-2" "program-3" "program-4" ...
#>  $ elbo     : num [1:21] Inf 1.06e+11 1.06e+11 1.06e+11 1.06e+11 ...

  • eta_prior: A \(K \times G\) matrix to denote the input of prior mean of eta. By calling learn.embedding.nmf, eta_prior is derived from nmf.

  • eta_post: A \(K \times G\) matrix to denote the MAP estimator of eta computed by EM.

  • omega: A \(N \times K\) matrix to denote the posterior mean of omega at eta_post, i.e., the weights of malignant gene programs in each bulk.

  • elbo: A numeric vector of ELBO (if compute.elbo = TRUE).

  • Lets check the progress


plot(ebd.res$elbo, xlab="EM cycle", ylab="-ELBO", type="l")

To run additional EM cycles, do the following. This will start additional EM cycles by initiating starting points from the previous EM.


ebd.res.2  <- learn.embedding(bp = bp.res,
                                  cycle = 10,
                                  EM.res = ebd.res,
                                  compute.elbo = T)

In cases where users have their own priors about malignant gene programs, e.g., those derived from developmental programs or other biological processes of interest, they may run embedding learning using a user-defined eta_prior.

#Not run
ebd.res.myEta  <- learn.embedding(bp = bp.res,
                                  eta_prior = my.eta, # A user supplied K-by-G matrix, at a raw count (non-log) scale.  
                                  cycle = 50,
                                  compute.elbo = T)

Downstream analysis

Potential downstream analysis can be performed using eta and omega are: * Clustering bulk samples by omega * Survival analysis and correlation with other clinical covariates using omega. * Correlation analysis between omega and theta_env (cell type fraction of non-malignant cells). * Gene set enrichment analysis for eta (See BayesPrism paper for details). * Select representative samples for each malignant program for downstream analysis, such as differential gene expression (See BayesPrism paper for details). * Deconvolve other bulk datasets using a reference GEP constructed by concatenating eta_post and psi_env.
